67","       1568":"1568","1523":"1523","1578":"1578","1576":"1576","1543":"1543","       1543":"1543","1573":"1573","13 Dec 1573":"13 December 1573","6 Aug 1573":"6 August 1573","26 AUG 1576":"26 August 1576","1648":"1648","1626":"1626","Of Saffron, Walden, Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Saffron Walden, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Swain</i>, <i>Swein</i> (Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>, <i>Sven</i>, from <i>sveinn</i> ‘lad’).","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swein</i> ‘servant, attendant; boy, young man’ (Old Norse <i>sveinn</i>). The word could also denote a swineherd or a peasant in general. The name was thoroughly confused with   Swan   1.","Irish: when not the English name, possibly an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Suibhne</b>; see   McSwain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Swan","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swon(e)</i>, northern Middle English <i>swan(e)</i> ‘swineherd; peasant; male servant’ (Old English <i>swān</i>). Compare   Swain   2, with which this name was thoroughly confused.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>swan</i>, <i>swon</i> ‘swan’. In the Middle Ages, the swan was taken as a symbol of false pride, and, according to Chaucer, jealousy. Compare   Kite  ,   Nightingale  , and   Pye  .","English: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Swan</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>. Compare   Swain   1."]},{"name":"Swainson","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Swain</i> (Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>; see   Swain  ) + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Swanson  .","English (northern): patronymic from Middle English <i>swein</i> ‘servant, attendant; boy, young man’ (Old Norse <i>sveinn</i>) + <i>-son</i>.","Americanized form of Swedish   Svensson   or of its cognate <b>Sveinsson</b>."]},{"name":"Swayne","meanings":["English: variant of   Swain  ."]},{"name":"Swaine","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Swain  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Swain was born in 1543, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Mr. Swaine, was 20 and her mother, Mrs Swaine, was 20. She married Henry May Maye in 1567, in Saffron Walden, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"       1543–":"154